di_data_file <- dietary_comp_by_country

di_data_file %>%
  select(everything()) %>%
  #  mutate(total_count = nrow(.) * ncol(.)) %>%
  summarise_all(list(
    NA_count = ~ sum(is.na(.)),
    Empty_count = ~ sum(. == "", na.rm = TRUE)
  )) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = everything(),
    names_to = "columns",
    values_to = "Empty_count"
  ) %>%
  filter(Empty_count != 0) %>%
  arrange(desc(Empty_count)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(
    y = reorder(columns, desc(Empty_count)),
    x = Empty_count,
    fill = Empty_count
  )) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_label(aes(label = Empty_count)) +
  annotate("text",
    x = Inf,
    y = Inf,
    label = paste(
      "total cells:",
      nrow(di_data_file) * ncol(di_data_file),
      " nrows",
      nrow(di_data_file)
    ),
    hjust = 1.1,
    vjust = 1.1,
    size = 3,
    color = "black"
  ) +
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "Spectral") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "a) Empty & NA Cell Count",
    x = "Number of empty cells",
    y = "Columns with empty or NA cells"
  )

Question 3 Clean kcal_source categories by removing any unnecessary information. Then clean all column names, and rename the column entity to country. Overwrite diet_comp_clean with your results. [Hint: youll probably have to use some regex to clean kcal_source categories]

diet_comp_clean <- diet_comp_clean %>%
  mutate(kcal_source = str_replace_all(kcal_source,
                                       pattern = "_", " ")) %>%
  mutate(kcal_source = str_replace_all(kcal_source, pattern = " fao 2017",
                                       "")) %>%

  clean_names()

missing_code_investigation <- diet_comp_clean %>%
  group_by(country, code) %>%

Question 6 Ok, we have no available country codes for Cabo Verde and the US. Is there anything in the data source about what these should be? No Ok, better find something online then. Google tells us theres something called ISO Alpha-3 codes which look pretty promising. Wait, whats that in your data folder? Read it in! Then find the missing codes!

country_codes <- read.csv(here("data/country_codes.csv")) %>% clean_names()

country_codes

country_codes %>%
  filter(country %in% c("United States", "Cape Verde")) %>%
  select(country, alpha_3_code)

Question 7 Using a suitable recoding function, fill in the missing (but now found) country codes. Overwrite diet_comp_clean again. Finally, check that there are now no missing values in the code column.

diet_comp_clean <- diet_comp_clean %>%
  mutate(code = case_when(
    country == "United States of America" ~ "USA",
    country == "Cabo Verde" ~ "CPV",
    TRUE ~ code
  ))

sum(is.na(diet_comp_clean$code))
[1] 0

Question 8 Note: Do NOT overwrite diet_comp_clean with the result of this question. Join the two datasets so only countries with matches in both are retained. Create a new logical column that is TRUE if the first two letters of code is the same as alpha_2_code.

names(diet_comp_clean)
[1] "country"         "code"            "year"            "kcal_source"     "avg_daily_kcals"
names(country_codes)
[1] "country"      "alpha_2_code" "alpha_3_code"
diet_comp_clean %>%
  inner_join(country_codes, by = "country") %>%
  distinct(country, code, alpha_2_code) %>%
  mutate(first_2_match = str_extract(code, "^[A-Z][A-Z]")) %>%
  mutate(same = first_2_match == alpha_2_code)

Question 10 Using uk_diet, create a new column that contains the difference in total calories between a year and the year before. Then find the year where there was the biggest positive difference and the biggest negative difference.

uk_diet %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(total_kcals = sum(avg_daily_kcals)) %>%
  arrange(year) %>%
  mutate(total_kcals_ly = lag(total_kcals)) %>%
  mutate(diff = total_kcals - total_kcals_ly)

Question 11 Back to diet_comp_clean again. For every year between 1990 and 2000 find which country got the most average daily calories from alcoholic beverages, i.e.you want to end up with one country per year.

diet_comp_clean %>%
  filter(year >= 1990 & year <= 2000) %>%
  filter(kcal_source == "alcoholic beverages") %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  slice_max(avg_daily_kcals) %>%
  select(year, country, avg_daily_kcals, kcal_source)

Question 12 Now write a function which finds the top calorie source for a user-specified vector of both countries and years. Then use your function to find the top calorie source for the UK and Zimbabwe in 1965, 1975, 1985, 1995 and 2005. Try out your function a few more times for countries/years that you find interesting! Also consider whether there are any limitations of your function.

top_calory <- function(data, countries, years) {
  data %>%
    filter(country %in% countries) %>%
    filter(year %in% years) %>%
    group_by(country, year) %>%
    slice_max(avg_daily_kcals)
}

top_calory(diet_comp_clean,
  countries = c("United Kingdom", "Zimbabwe"),
  years = seq(1965, 2005, 10)
)

countries_start_b <- diet_comp_clean %>%

  pull()

top_calory(diet_comp_clean,
  countries = countries_start_b,
  years = 1970
)
